?    The Worst-Case weather conditions which were used for this scenario are uncommon;
?    Industry and ASME standards were followed for the manufacture and quality control of the High Pressure Ammonia Receiver.  U-1A manufacturer?s data reports and State Permit will be on file the facility;
?    The Control Pressure Receiver is located inside the Engine Room and cannot be impacted by a vehicle.  The Engine Room is kept locked and cannot be accessed except by authorized personnel;
?    Ammonia is not corrosive in this service and the Control Pressure Receiver will be maintained in good condition and inspected at least annually by the personnel and every 4 years by the insurance carrier or by the State;
?    Dual safety relief valves limit operating pressure in the Control Pressure Receiver; and
?    The facility will have a training program designed to ensure that the system is operated by experienced and qualified personnel.

Several alternative (more likely) release scenarios at the facility involve the following:

?    Release of 504 pounds over a period of 8 hours due to a ?pin? hole in a pipe on the roof.  The ammonia lines will be painted or insulated to prevent rusting or corrosion and inspected annually.
?    Release of 1090 pounds over a period of 60 minutes due to a flange gasket leaking at one of the connections at a solenoid valve or strainer located on the roof.
?    Release of 138 pounds over a one minute period due to the rupture of the ammonia receiving hose during the a charging of the system.

None of the above alternate scenarios would pose a hazard to the public at a distance of more that .1 miles.

The likelihood of an alternative release scenario is minimized for the following reasons:

